article.headline: Alcorn St. 32, Jackson St. 31
article.story: JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Chris Walker's touchdown pass to Nate Hughes late in the fourth quarter lifted Alcorn State to a 32-31 win over Jackson State on Saturday. Jackson State (6-5, 5-4 Southwestern Athletic Conference) had a chance win the game, but Eric Perri he missed a 40-yard field goal as time expired. Perri had made a 44-yarder in the third quarter. Walker passed for three touchdowns during the game, including the 3-yard shot to Hughes with just 1:54 left in regulation. Alcorn (5-5, 4-4 SWAC) overcame a 28-14 deficit in the second half with a 71-yard punt return by Hughes, a field goal and a safety. The Tigers led 31-26 with 13:09 left to play. Walker, who opened the game with a 55-yard touchdown pass to Ocie Brown Jr., marched his team 94 yards down the field on a game-winning drive that was capped by Hughes' third touchdown of the night. Walker finished the game 15-of-22 for 219 yards and Alcorn beat the Tigers for the fourth straight time. Jackson State has lost four of its last five games, but got its first winning season since 2002. Jimmy Oliver scored on a 4-yard touchdown run for Jackson State and threw a 16-yard touchdown pass to Carlos Simpson. Dorian Smith scored two first-quarter touchdowns and Jackson State finished with 405 yards of offense.
